segments.text: And...
I came to A&M after World War II.
I went down to North Carolina State where I got my BS degree after the war.
And Dr. Lindsey had taught there before the war, and they suggested that I might write him to get into graduate school.
So I wrote him in.
Were you, excuse me, were you from North Carolina?
Around Statesville, yes.
See, I did, went to Mars Hill Junior College.
I got an A.B.
there, a Bachelor of Chemical Engineering from North Carolina State in 1943.
And then I was in the Navy for four years.
I worked for Burlington Mills for one year.
Then I decided I really wanted to go back to graduate school.
So then I went back down to North Carolina State and talked with the professors there.
And I had missed Lindsey because he had taught there while I was in the service, I guess.
I think just one year or so, one or two years.
He wasn't teaching there when I finished in 43.
And he wasn't there when I went back after the war.
He'd come out here.
And so they suggest I write him, and I wrote him, and he wanted me to come out here to go to graduate school.
So I elected to come.
And so I came out here then in 48, spring of 48.
as to do the work on the master's degree.
And then I got my master's here in 49 under Bill Murdock, P.G.
Murdock, who had come and got hired sometime after the war.
He'd been the shell developer at Emeryville.
And so I did both my master's and my Ph.D. under him.
Well, in the first area, I worked under on my master's degree.
I did it on distillation, and it was a mathematical description of distillation columns using the finite difference calculus.
And then for my Ph.D., I worked on chemical adsorption.
I did a thesis on that, or a dissertation.
And I actually finished it and got my degree in 1953.
I started teaching for the department in 1952.
That's one of my GI bills right now, so I needed some additional support.
And so I began teaching then in 1952, and then finished up in 1953.
And I started teaching in 1952 as an instructor.
And then in 1949, I made
Let's see, I'm a full professor.
In 1949, I got the master's degree.
In 53, I got the PhD.
And then, I guess it was about 59, I got the full professor.
In 64, I was named head of the department.
You moved along fast.
You moved along rapidly.
Well, there wasn't many people back then.
There wasn't much incentive to come to A&M to pay you a support back in those days.
Do you remember, you were still under Lindsey.
Do you remember much about Lindsey and the department when you first came into it?
number of people here, and the general thrust or character of the department?
Were they petroleum types, or were they- what were we doing mostly?
Well, at that time, he was building a department, trying to build a department at that time.
Very difficult for him because every time he got some, they'd go- Moved on.
Moved on.
Jobs were good.
He had G.L.
Fair, who'd been with Mobile during the war, and A.M. Platt, both been with Mobile.
They were teaching.
And Bob Andrews, who was in the service, was one of the professors, and so was F.F.
Bishop.
Yeah, I've heard a lot of people mention him.
He was with the department then.
And he was a full professor.
And W.D.
Harris was a full professor.
Yeah.
I interviewed John there.
Oh, you did?
Yesterday, yeah.
He's been playing today.
Yeah.
And so...
But actually though, let's see, about the time I got my Ph.D., Dr. Murdock quit and went with Dow.
And G.L.
Fair quit about that time and took a job as associate editor or assistant editor or something, oil and gas journal.
And A.M. Platt went out to Hanford
all about the same time.
And then Bill Murdock, my director, quit about the time I got my degree and went to Dallas.
And so, at that time, that pretty little well left us with Dr. Harris, Dr. Lindsay.
Bishop died in 1955.
So we were down to Dr. Harris, Dr. Bishop, no I meant Dr. Harris, Lindsay, and I guess that was it.
Bill Harris, was he around?
No, we pulled him in to help do some teaching.
We also got graduate students to help do some teaching.
We just didn't have the staff to do it.
So, we were trying to do a graduate program and try to teach young grads, and it was just the salaries they were paying back there.
Actually, the V.S.
were doing as well, if not a little better.
I remember one of the persons went to work, and I started teaching, got more than 90 of the Ph.D. V.S.
Yeah, I've heard someone else mention that before.
So, it was really hard to hire people back then.
So, we rocked along.
Was sort of the thrust of the department at that time keyed in for petrochemical?
Well, it really wasn't much different.
It was to some extent, but not all that much.
We were one of the first ones to establish a portion in chemical engineering kinetics analysis.
This was done, this was a good group of people, so they had some of that.
emphasis there, but it wasn't all that much.
How about with agriculture, with the cotton, was it cotton research laboratory?
Cotton seed products, research laboratory, that was kind of under, the doctor's worked over there part of the time.
But we were pretty well separated from that at one time.
I think they decided they wanted to run it, the experiment station.
So they took it from- Probably Benson.
No, it was before that.
So they kind of pulled it out from under Lindsey and them.
But Dr. Harry still worked over there.
Then I've forgotten a long time, somewhere in that time, Bill
Bill Harris came to help teach, and Dr. Davis, he came also to assist in the teaching, and we later hired both of those.
I think both of them were working on degrees, and so they taught some while they were working on their degrees.
And that was during the 50s.
And then in 64,
Dr. Lindsay stepped down and said,
Did Lindsey stay on and teach for a while?
Two or three years.
I let him stay as long as he wanted to.
He was elected not to teach any longer.
I don't think he taught but a couple of years.
It wasn't very much.
Well, you really stepped into the headship at a prime time, didn't you?
Really, 64 should have been sort of the beginning of the boom.
Well, actually what happened there, even at the beginning of what happened then,
It was John Connolly that was the one that really did more for Texas Education than anybody we've met.
He got some salaries, and we got 30% increases there two or three years ago.
I'm not sure we've ever been much better off relatively then than we ought to have since that time.
And that was all due to John Connolly, so that was when it started moving.
I came here in 69, and there was a big
There's lots of new people about that time, from 64 through 69, really.
Yeah, but there are not too many people my age here.
Or none of them now.
But I mean, all during my career, there weren't many.
Most of those went to industry.
Yeah, right.
Engineering and alternatives were so attractive.
But never that way in history, I don't think.
We were grateful for anything.
Well, that's good to know, though, that Connolly, you know, like... Oh, yeah, he was the one, and he made all the difference in the world in Texas education.
Up until that time, they were all saying, well, the legislature won't give us this, the legislature won't give us that.
But he got out and convinced people that they needed to put some money into education, and the legislature, and they did, and that's when it started really going.
What about the, on the higher levels at A&M, Gilchrist, Harrington, and Rudder?
Well, you see, when I came here, Dr. Bolton was executive vice president, and Gilchrist was president, and that made Gilchrist, I guess he was chancellor then.
Yeah, for a short time.
Yeah, and then Bolton was executive vice president.
And then Tom Harrington was teaching over, when I first came here, he was teaching over at the base.
That's right, he was in charge of that NX program for a while.
He got a B.S.
degree in Company Engineering back in 21.
But then they made Tom president, and while he was president,
I see Morgan came in.
That's right, two years.
They had quite a squabble.
And eventually they let Morgan go.
I believe they made Morgan president and Tom became the chancellor.
Then they let Morgan go and then Tom came back and was president.
He's president two times.
And chancellor, yeah.
Yeah, well, I think it just dropped to chancellor.
Then I guess they must have established the, he got Rutter in, and they eventually made Tom chancellor, I guess, again.
And then Rutter was president.
And then finally, they kept taking Tom's duties away from him the first thing he knew.
He had, Rudder took it all over and became president.
That's right, he ended up in charge of that foreign affair.
Oh yeah, they just sent him on a world tour.
I remember that.
That was the kiss-off.
That was his reward for retiring.
I don't know why Rudder in such a hurry only had a few months until Harrington retired anyway.
But anyway, that's the way that turned out.
Now all of that really probably had little or no impact.
Well, it did.
Actually, Rudder.
That's what I'm getting at.
Rudder did more for the university, I think, than any president we've ever had.
There's been none of them, and he's been close to where he was.
And I think that he was one of the better ones we've ever had.
Although, I didn't think he could cut it when they put him in.
Well, I know no one did, you know.
When I was doing that centennial history, Rutter was president, and I talked to him in the interview, and everybody I talked to said, well, this is an unlike candidate to Virginia.
And, in fact, I used that comment in the pictorial history or something, which I'm revising this year.
Ms. Rutter is still mad about that comment.
that he was not qualified for the job, you know, or something like that that I made.
She called me not too long ago and told me about it.
I'm just trying to make a point that he was an unlikely man who did a miraculous job as president.
Well, you know, people kind of felt that way.
He had his training in physical education.
In the land office and sheriff at one year or something.
Then he came in here and
But he really did a tremendous job as President, and then I was, see I was an apartment head most of the time, but when Benson became Dean, Barlow left.
I was here when Barlow was Dean.
Barlow left and then Benson became Dean.
And Dean, he was, Dr. Lindsey worked under Benson two or three years before I was made head.
And then we didn't go out and search.
Benson just called me over to his office one day and said... That's the way the world works.
He said, would you take the head of the department?
He said, you don't have to answer.
Right now, you can think it over a day or two.

And I thought about it a little while, and finally decided, well, I'm interested in the work we were doing, so I finally decided, well, I can probably get about as much done on what I want to do if I'm here as I could if we got somebody else in here and had me doing what he wanted me to do.
So I decided to go ahead and take it.
Then I just came very near asking to try to get Lindsey to take it one more year.
Good idea.
And he was, so I knew Rutter real well.
When people would come in and get the department money, he would always go to his office.
So I knew him real well.
How'd you and Vincent get along?
Oh, just fine.
Well, Calhoun was dean for a little while, not long.
But Lindsey was head of the department, and Calhoun didn't.
Yeah, I would have talked to Dr. Calhoun, but he's still in town anyway.
Do you feel like Benson, when he, one thing he did was separate, or rather integrate, the research, teaching,
And that was about your time, wasn't it, when you were department head?
That's a hard thing to do.
And he made a good effort at it.
Well, what do you think?
Well, I think it was integrated certainly better.
I worked under two different conditions.
Barlow was dean, Mellon was head of the experiment station.
And I had two bosses, and each one of them thought
And about half time on each one, each one of them thought I was working for them full time.
Yeah, that's what happened, I know.
And so, and they didn't get along.
Barlow and Mello didn't get along.
They wrote letters to one another on the same floor.
One of them had an office on one end of that old Aerospace building and the other one had an office on the other end.
I know that.
I reported the both of them.
That's where it happened, right off.
But basically though, that system is still, that's continued.
No, no, they've changed it.
Then when Benson became dean, they put it back, put both the Experiment Station and the academic part of it, College of Engineering, all under one person.
And that way it can be integrated.
Because he can say, well,
Let's see, if your grant's out, I guess we'd just put you on teaching.
Provide more flexibility.
Then when he, Benson, retired, they went back to the other system and they put Page in there.
He had the academic part, and Skip, I mean, no, Page had the academic part.
I should know that.
Yeah, Skip Porter.
Yeah, Skip Porter was the tease.
That went on for two or three years, and then they got, the next time they put it back together, and that's the way it is right now.
I know there's always been problems.
But it's better back together.
You can still run it down in one office.
Although, theoretically, the stations isn't on the same par as a state institution as a university.
Yeah, I know it.
But it's really better run through the academic, because you mix it up a little better.
I think that was part of the rub with Porter.
Porter apparently had connections straight to the legislature.
Well, he had all the money.
Old Bates didn't have any money.
As department head, when you came in, how would you describe the department, and what did you assume would be your primary effort or direction or means?
Well, first of all, we had these staff members just before I come in, we hired two, who were
Dr. Durbin and Dr. Hupin.
And in all of those years back there, the southern universities were always, were already behind with research.
The northern universities were already into it.
So we, I can see we had to do a lot of catch up.
And so what I tried to do was hire young professors and bring them in as assistant professors.
And most of those people that are on the staff now except the recent hires, I ended up hiring them all.
Including Ray, you hired Ray.
I hired Ray, I hired Darby, I hired Booker, I hired Ackerman, I hired Ackerman, Hanson,
Did you call home?
And we made the reservation.
Okay, good.
And just to close it, it may bother them out there.
Is the thrust of the department changing in terms of academics between 64 and 87?
Well, I'll tell you one of the things that I've tried to do all the time, two or three times I've tried to do.
One, I've tried to keep, you can just go all inches on research, and I've tried to keep those people walking that path where you're trying to do a good job at both levels.
And we have these undergraduate students that we've got a responsibility to do a good job with them, and also try to build the graduate school.
So we had two responsibilities.
Another thing, I've been through all those lean years.
Another thing I've tried to do, and I think I was pretty successful at it, because most people were on 12-month salaries.
And I kept juggling around one way or another, where everybody got to pay 12 months out of a year, and I pampered them.
Outsiders would say, well, maybe I pampered them too much.
But I tried to keep that going the whole time.
So, and also I tried to, didn't try to do everything.
Lindsey used to try to do everything himself.
Yeah, I know.
He even checked the student program of the students.
He worked and did all these kind of things.
Milton used to read every thesis and every report.
Yeah, so what I did was try to divide that up to where I could continue to do some research.
So all the time I was head of the department I also continued to teach.
I taught one or two courses a day.
And also I wrote over a hundred technical papers and six books.
I've written one since I got through.
And so I tried to stay
What was your research primarily?
I did an awful lot because I could not do much experimental research being in an office and see.
I just hit the wave of computers.
So what we were looking at was how do you solve these simple engineering problems on computers.
So that was the type of problem we were looking at.
How did Don Harris and Ruth
home yesterday.
He was showing me his new computer.
He's really loaded with some good equipment.
So this is basically what I'm trying to do.
We need to build a graduate program.
We also need to keep a good undergraduate program.
I had to keep those people trying to do a good job teaching and research.
And so that was kind of what we had to do there, I saw.
And we did fairly well at it.
Those people that have come in now, some of them didn't fan out as well as others in the search, but a lot of them have done real well.
And I hired Olsby also.
There's another one.
I hired Hall.
Hall and Olsby.
You've looked up all of them.
I would guess.
chemical engineering was one of the most... Dan Benson tells me when I visit him that we were the best department.
Well, I started saying that.
You know, I really did.
In the sense that, well, you know, I knew Troy Crawford really well.
As far as mechanical and the old stable line departments, they were here and they were good.
But in terms of expansion and being at the edge of... We tried to keep, I tried to keep something that was going in all these different fields.
Of development.
We tried to do it with young people.
I didn't.
I resisted.
They were always wanting me to hire these experts to come in, and I resisted that.
You know, that's a problem.
Time and again.
Time and again, because what happens is they come in and they get all the goodies.
Yeah, that's right.
And you see these, uh...
This Bokker's came in wanting to go to work for me.
And I talked with him a little bit, and I decided, hell, let's just, uh...
He would just be overwhelming my students.
I mean, my young faculty.
They just can't...
He would just try to overwhelm them to where they'd be nothing.
The big department can tolerate it, but we can't.
That's really a problem, and you see a lot of these guys being brought in, especially in the last, what, 10 or 15 years, distinguished whatever they are, and they come in and they don't do anything.
Yeah, they want to buy everything.
And I thought, what's the real measure of accomplishments is to hire a young man and then have him make a contribution.
Make him have, then let him have contributions.
And so if you can hire the young people, bring them in.
And also, you've got a pretty good chance, because they're hungry.
That's right.
No question about it.
And so bring the young people in and let them do it.
Now, again, between 64 and 87, roughly right now,
Was there a, how about your students?
What kind of students are you getting and how would you describe them?
Where are they going after they get out of here?
Oh you know it, well they've always, generally the only year we didn't have jobs was because that's when we had the biggest glass thing somewhere along there.
It was hard for me to say, you know,
We've had good students.
I'll tell you the best students that I think I've ever ran across were, don't know that they were the smartest, but it was the World War II veterans that came back here.
And it wasn't because they were necessarily any smarter.
All they wanted to know was just what is required.
Or they'd go after it.
And they'd do it really first class.
And I think...

there's an indication that students are not working as hard they're well prepared maybe they are i don't know um i know they're not as good as attending classes no they sure not i remain i see that yeah in my class and uh i just kind of feel like well if you it's your business you're paying the money if you don't come in here and get it i'm not going to force you to yeah
But as far as being prepared, they're well prepared.
In fact, this would be hard to see for us to some extent because we get better students out of high school.
Yeah, that's true, too.
If you get smart students, it's hard to screw them up.
They're going to be good.
In spite of all the teaching that you do, they're still going to be smart students in the end.
They're about as sharp as they ever were.
They're sharp as they ever were.
And they have had more, probably better preparation.
The thing is, I don't think they work as hard as they tend to.
And I don't think they're as thorough, won't be as thorough as they used to be.
But they're sharp.
Don or Bill Harris, one of them, was talking about the change that they have seen in that there's less hands-on engineering involved in construction and this kind of thing.
Do you see that?
Or is that even a...
I'm sure there is from the old days.
Well, actually, what's happening is that nobody's got much hands on anymore in the plants.
Even when you're out there, yeah.
Yeah, because it's all done in a control room where it needs to go out there and be changed valves.
Well, that's probably what they were talking about.
But now you turn the valve, you push the buttons, and you let the computer up, and you don't understand what you're doing.
I don't know if that was Donald or Bill or one of them.
But they still have to go out there and look at what's out there.
And I don't know if there's really that much difference, because see, they never could do too much, because the union people were the only ones that could turn down anything, unless you had a strike.
And so, I don't know if there's that much.
There's a lot of difference.
The big difference in industry now is they're pulling off a lot of the technical work that used to be done.
It's not being done inside the industry anymore.
They're contracting.
They're contracting all their design work.
They don't even have design forces.
They've slimmed down to where the people working for them just kind of manage projects.
They don't actually do the detailed design.
They've got a few people around, but engineering firms are picking that up.
Do you see more of your STEM-E graduates going into that kind of work?
I'm not really sure because I'm not following employment right now.
Well, there's a lot more changing now.
I imagine there's a lot more changing around.
But I don't think all this downsizing has been good.
What's happened is that you can get into a situation and just keep cutting down and keep cutting down.
I saw an article in the Post the other day.
One of the stock brokers had come out and said that initially they were vapor.
companies and help rate if they downsized.
He said that was no longer.

They had decided that they'd done already too much of that, and then he told, this was editorial, and then the guy told the story about the Scotsman with the horse, and he found out that, decided, well, I'm just beating this horse, I'm just better speed with it, so he cut it.
Then he said, well, he seems to be getting along with that all right.
So he cut it again, and he kept cutting and he kept cutting.
Finally, he wasn't feeding no horse anything.
He died.
So that's just the moral of it.
You can overdo it.
But this is payout.
The industries do go for payout.
Yeah, and they seem to be pushed heavily by the financial community.
They're pushed by them, and also they're pushed by others.
If others start doing it, they start doing it.
I never did understand that until I was talking to a fellow one day, and he pointed out to me, the petroleum company, production people were particularly bad about that.
One of them started drilling over here, all of them.
All of them running over there trying to get a lease, you know, at the same time.
And he said, well, just think of yourself as a plantation board of directors.
He said, you know the competition's running out doing this.
And you chose not to go in that direction.
Then it turns out that what they did was real successful and what you did failed.
What do you think your board's going to say?
You dumbass.
Watch those people over there.
You mean you couldn't see where they were going?
That's the same with mergers and...
all this kind of thing.
But I think it's readjusting, and they're going more toward a team effort.
Trying to go toward a team effort now, maybe this thing, but I think there's a lot of tendency toward cutting back on friends' benefits.
One of the things that I'm afraid of is
The same way with the universities.
Once you get management too much in control, they tend to start trying to in effect the amounts of this running over the people.
The same thing with the universities now, getting this going to revoke tenure.
See, I was with this, I helped get in this.
Tenure system?
Well, not the tenure system as much as that grading system for students.
I remember very well old Samson worked it out, and I supported him on it because I felt like everybody was just
swearing and declaring this will never be used for salaries.
I had some of these old guys around here say, I'm against that.
The administration will be using that for salaries.
No, no, they said they wouldn't.
You know, they'll keep their word.
And you see what's happened.
That's right.
Yeah, well, it's come from that.
Because if they'd have kept it like it was initially, it would have been all right, just for the profit of the city.
Yeah.
But there's too much resistance there to use it.
So that's a weakness of it.
When you retired in 1987, did you go consulting?
No, I set up this institute.
And I still teach one course, but I run this institute that's a non-profit charitable corporation.
I'm president of it.
It operates just like the Research Foundation.
We are not part of the university.
Do you have some literature or brochure?
Let me carry some of that away with me.
I'll give you a whole packet of it.
And so that's what we're getting out now, another mailing.
So what I've done is looked at chemicals, cancer, safety in the workplace, hazardous waste incineration, chlorine.
Speaking of that, Don Harris again was talking about his son, his son named William Sawyer.
Yeah, he studied.
Well, I think that's a...
I don't think so at all.
I think that... Well, I don't think so.
No, I think that they both had the same kind of cancer.
I think that's an inheritance.
I think that was an inheritance.
But actually we found that the industry had about 9% fewer lower cancer rates than the general public.
We had this study done outside the university with an epidemiologist.
with the Texas School of Public Health.
And it turned out that they were 9% less, most of them were less statistically significant.
Any of those that were elevated, none of them were statistically significant.
So, and these were the people that were exposed more heavier than Don's son.
They were the ones that were exposed.
Back there, starting in the 30s, 40s, and 50s, when there was no limitation on anything, the smoke was just billowing out of those tanks.
And everybody looked on that as a sign of production, so they were full steam ahead.
Well, that's good.
That's a good thing.
And then we did one on chlorine after that.
The Texas chemical industry out here in the future is one we've done now.
And we're doing two right at this time.
One of them is on hormesis.
We've hired that one done, but it's a property of a chemical to be toxic to high doses and therapeutic to low.
And you see all medicines... Like snake poison or something.
Well, all medicines are... Yeah, they are.
That's right.
And so there's no reason to suspect other chemists don't have.
So what I'm going to do is see how widespread this is.
Good.
Now you can do this stuff.
And then I'm doing more.
Who are you going to?
May I ask?
Most of the food and drug administration?
Oh, you mean...
Oh, it was made mostly for the companies.
By the companies?
Uh-huh.
They got a membership fee.
We got about 80 to 70 or 80 members.
And then I go out and speak to, I speak to Rotary Clubs and Lions Clubs.
I've spoken about once or twice a week to all of them, to the Rotary Clubs down in the Houston area.
Well, that's great.
That's exciting.
That's a good thing to be doing.
So, right now, we're getting out two or three mailings.
One of them is the proceedings last spring at the annual meeting, which was on this topic of Hermesius.
We're getting out.
a review of, I'll give you a copy.
Yeah, if you will.

I did a little review on background on it, just an introduction to it, and I spoke for about 22 o'clock that night the other day on that, just in the form of my sending it out to some select members of the Institute.
Then I had the review here not long ago, this book, Our Stolen Future,
It's a book that's come out that, well, they're, what, basically... Pollution environment?
Yeah, well, see, they start out with heavy doses have done all this damage to them, wildlife and so on.
Yeah.
Therefore, jump all the way over to the low-dose exposures is harmful.
Well, we don't really know what that is.
But they presented this back, and it's the way it's written up.
So you want to abolish this one?
And so what I'm doing at this point, yeah, and so it's just that we ought to do more testing to find out exactly where we are.
So that was it.
I'll tell you what, we probably did well running over there.
All right.
Great.
